```java
public class User {
    private List<String> roles;
    private List<String> permissions;

    public User() {
        roles = new ArrayList<>();
        permissions = new ArrayList<>();
    }

    public void addRole(String role) {
        roles.add(role);
    }

    public void addPermission(String permission) {
        permissions.add(permission);
    }

    private boolean contains(List<String> list, String item) {
        return list.contains(item);
    }

    public boolean isAdmin() {
        return contains(roles, "ADMIN");
    }

    public boolean hasPermission(String permission) {
        return contains(permissions, permission);
    }
}
```

**Explanation:** In this refactored version, a private helper method `contains` is introduced to encapsulate the logic for checking the presence of an element in a list. This eliminates the duplication of similar logic in `isAdmin` and `hasPermission` methods, making the code more concise and easier to maintain. With this change, any modification needed for checking list contents can be done in one place, improving the code's extensibility and reducing the risk of errors.

