A common strategy to address the Long Method code smell is to break down the method into smaller, more manageable helper methods, each responsible for a single piece of functionality. This improves readability, maintainability, and makes the code easier to test and debug. Here's an example:

**Original Code with Long Method:**
```java
public class OrderProcessor {
    public void processOrder(Order order) {
        // Validate order
        if (order == null || order.getItems().isEmpty()) {
            throw new IllegalArgumentException("Order cannot be null or empty");
        }
        // Calculate total price
        double total = 0;
        for (Item item : order.getItems()) {
            total += item.getPrice() * item.getQuantity();
        }
        // Apply discount
        if (order.hasDiscount()) {
            total -= order.getDiscount().apply(total);
        }
        // Confirm order
        order.setStatus("Confirmed");
        // Log order processing
        System.out.println("Order processed: " + order.getId());
    }
}
```

