double calculateTotalPrice(List<Item> items, boolean isDiscountApplicable) {
  double totalPrice = 0;
  for (Item item : items) {
    totalPrice += item.getPrice();
  }
  if (isDiscountApplicable) {
    totalPrice = totalPrice - (totalPrice * 0.1);
  }
  return totalPrice;
}
```

**Answer:**  
Refactor the code to improve its structure and readability by extracting the discount calculation into a separate method:

```java
double calculateTotalPrice(List<Item> items, boolean isDiscountApplicable) {
  double totalPrice = sumPrices(items);
  if (isDiscountApplicable) {
    totalPrice = applyDiscount(totalPrice);
  }
  return totalPrice;
}

private double sumPrices(List<Item> items) {
  double total = 0;
  for (Item item : items) {
    total += item.getPrice();
  }
  return total;
}

private double applyDiscount(double price) {
  return price * 0.9;
}
```

**Explanation:**  
The original code suffers from a Long Method code smell, where the method `calculateTotalPrice` is responsible for summing item prices and applying a discount. This can make the method difficult to read and maintain. By extracting `sumPrices` and `applyDiscount`, we separate concerns, making the code more modular and improving readability. Each method now performs a single responsibility, adhering to the Single Responsibility Principle.

