```java
class Customer {
  private String name;
  private String address;
  private List<Order> orders;

  public void printCustomerDetails() {
    System.out.println("Name: " + name);
    System.out.println("Address: " + address);
    for (Order order : orders) {
      System.out.println("Order Total: " + order.calculateTotal());
    }
  }
}
```

Refactor the code to address the code smells identified, and explain the changes made.

### Answer:

Refactored Code:

```java
class Customer {
  private String name;
  private String address;
  private List<Order> orders;

  public void printCustomerDetails() {
    System.out.println("Name: " + name);
    System.out.println("Address: " + address);
    printOrderTotals();
  }

  private void printOrderTotals() {
    for (Order order : orders) {
      System.out.println("Order Total: " + order.calculateTotal());
    }
  }
}
```

Explanation:

The original code snippet exhibits the Long Method code smell. The `printCustomerDetails` method is performing multiple tasks: printing customer details and iterating over orders to print their totals. By extracting the order printing logic into a separate method named `printOrderTotals`, we address this code smell. This improves the readability and maintainability of the code by ensuring that each method has a single responsibility, adhering to the Single Responsibility Principle.

