```java
class ShoppingCart {
  List<Item> items;

  public double calculateTotal() {
    double total = 0;
    for (Item item : items) {
      total += item.price * item.quantity;
    }
    return total;
  }
}

class ReceiptPrinter {
  public static void printReceipt(ShoppingCart cart) {
    System.out.println("Receipt:");
    for (Item item : cart.items) {
      System.out.println(item.name + " x " + item.quantity + ": " + (item.price * item.quantity));
    }
    System.out.println("Total: " + cart.calculateTotal());
  }
}
```

**Explanation**: This refactoring separates the concerns by moving the printReceipt function to a new class, ReceiptPrinter. The ShoppingCart class maintains its focus on handling cart-related operations, while the ReceiptPrinter class takes care of the presentation logic. This improves the code's modularity and readability.

