public class UserService {
    private DatabaseConnection dbConnection;

    public UserService(DatabaseConnection dbConnection) {
        this.dbConnection = dbConnection;
    }

    public User getUser(int id) {
        connectAndPerform(() -> dbConnection.fetchUserById(id));
    }

    public void saveUser(User user) {
        connectAndPerform(() -> dbConnection.saveUser(user));
    }

    private <T> T connectAndPerform(Supplier<T> action) {
        dbConnection.connect();
        try {
            return action.get();
        } finally {
            dbConnection.disconnect();
        }
    }

    private void connectAndPerform(Runnable action) {
        dbConnection.connect();
        try {
            action.run();
        } finally {
            dbConnection.disconnect();
        }
    }
}
```

**Explanation:** The original code suffers from the code smell known as "Duplicated Code" because both `getUser` and `saveUser` methods repeat the `connect` and `disconnect` logic. The refactored version introduces a method `connectAndPerform`, which abstracts the connection handling logic. This method uses Java's functional interfaces, `Supplier` and `Runnable`, to allow passing the specific database operations as lambda expressions. This refactoring removes duplication and enhances the maintainability and clarity of the `UserService` class by isolating the connection logic.

